<statement>
<p>A triangle has sides with lengths <m>\displaystyle{a}={7.00}</m>, <m>\displaystyle{b}={7.91}</m>, and <m>\displaystyle{c}={8.59}</m>. Calculate all of the angles of this triangle.</p>
<p>A=<fillin characters="4"/> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{a}={7.00}</m>)</p>
<p>
  B=<fillin characters="4"/> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{b}={7.91}</m>)</p>
<p>
  C=<fillin characters="4"/> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{c}={8.59}</m>)</p>
<p>Round to two decimal places.</p>


</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li>50</li><li>59.95</li><li>71.69</li></ul></p><p>Because we have all three sides, we can use the law of cosines for the first angle.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{7}^{{2}}={7.91}^{{2}}+{8.59}^{{2}}-{2}{\left({7.91}\right)}{\left({8.59}\right)}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{49}={62.5681}+{73.7881}-{135.8938}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{87.3562}=-{135.8938}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{0.64282697223862}={\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{A}={49.997055840858}={50}</m>.</p>
<p>For a second angle, we can use the shorter law of sines.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{\sin{{\left({49.997055840858}\right)}}}}{{7.00}}=\frac{{\sin{{\left({B}\right)}}}}{{7.91}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{0.29969264039433}={\sin{{\left({B}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{B}={\arcsin{{\left(-{0.29969264039433}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{B}={59.950475312473}\approx{59.95}</m></p>
<p>The third angle we can calculate using the angle sum property.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{49.997055840858}+{59.950475312473}+{C}={180}^{\circ}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{C}={71.690331206141}\approx{71.69}</m></p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>